Body: The cloneBoard function performs a shallow clone of tile objects. If tiles contain nested objects (like rectAnchor, cellMergeCounts, etc.), these nested objects will be shared between the original and cloned board, which could lead to unintended mutations during simulation. Consider using a deep clone utility or explicitly cloning nested properties to ensure complete isolation between simulation and game state.
```suggestion
 * Deep-clone an individual tile, including its nested objects.
 *
 * This avoids sharing nested state (e.g., rectAnchor, cellMergeCounts) between
 * the live game board and the simulation board.
 */
function cloneTile(tile) {
    if (!tile) return null;

    // Start with a shallow clone of all primitive and reference properties.
    const cloned = { ...tile };

    // Explicitly deep-clone known nested objects to avoid shared references.
    if (tile.rectAnchor && typeof tile.rectAnchor === "object") {
        cloned.rectAnchor = { ...tile.rectAnchor };
    }

    if (tile.cellMergeCounts && typeof tile.cellMergeCounts === "object") {
        cloned.cellMergeCounts = { ...tile.cellMergeCounts };
    }

    // If tiles track their merge origins as an array of tiles, clone them too.
    if (Array.isArray(tile.mergedFrom)) {
        cloned.mergedFrom = tile.mergedFrom.map((t) => cloneTile(t));
    }

    return cloned;
}

/**
 * Deep-clone the board (2D array of tile objects).
 */
function cloneBoard(board) {
    return board.map((row) => row.map((tile) => cloneTile(tile)));
```

